<fix subject="frame stutter">
	<problem (>
		Spinning triangle shows mild frame stutter. Not aliasing (edges) —
		it's temporal. Guessed vsync/double-buffering first; both already
		handled in our code, so that was wrong.
	<investigation (>
		Instrumented the loop: split each frame into render-submit time vs
		swap/present block time, printed once per second.
		- render (our GL submission): avg ~0.08ms, dead flat  -> NOT us
		- swap (vsync/present block):  avg ~10ms, max pegged ~17.00ms
		120Hz panel: 8.33ms = 1 refresh, 16.67ms = 2 refreshes. swap is
		bimodal between 1 and 2 intervals -> uneven present cadence.
		Also saw 447-499 fps bursts at startup = impossible under real
		vsync, so vsync isn't cleanly capping either.
	<root-cause (>
		Presentation/vsync cadence on the deprecated macOS GL-on-Metal path
		is irregular. NOT our code, NOT performance, NOT the dt math. Known
		limitation of legacy OpenGL on Apple Silicon.
	<solution (>
		Option 1 (accept for now): keep &glfwSwapInterval(1);, add a dt
		clamp (if dt > 0.1, dt = 0.1) so a long stall pauses motion instead
		of lurching. Residual micro-stutter is a platform artifact.
	<not-the-fix (>
		"Fix Your Timestep" (fixed timestep + interpolation) addresses
		simulation/variable-dt judder, NOT presentation jitter — wouldn't
		help this symptom.
	</>

